  "tips": [
    {
      "type": "lead",
      "text": "The last of the letters today, and one mark of punctuation. X sits below S on the left ring finger, Z below A on the left pinky - the far corner of the bottom row, the deepest reach you will make. Take them slowly. There is no prize for hurrying the hardest keys on the board."
    },
    {
      "type": "drop",
      "text": "B and N are index reaches down and inward: B to the left index, N to the right. And the semicolon - that quiet, underrated mark - rests right under the right pinky on the home row, no reach at all. A useful little key; learn it once and it serves you for life."
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "icon": "🖐",
      "title": "Finish what you started",
      "text": "These are the letters most people never train, and it shows the moment a Z or an X turns up - the hands stall and the eyes drop. You are about to be done with that for good. Strike each one cleanly and return home. Then the whole alphabet is yours, with nothing left to hunt for."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": "x x x x x x x x x x z z z z z z z z z z",
      "finger": "pink",
      "title": "Left corner: X and Z",
      "hint": "Left ring drops from S to X; left pinky drops from A to Z. The deepest reach."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "target": "b b b b b b b b b b n n n n n n n n n n",
      "finger": "blue",
      "title": "Index: B and N",
      "hint": "Left index reaches down to B; right index down to N. Strike and home."
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
      "kind": "drill",
      "unit": ";",
      "baseReps": 20,
      "keys": [";"],
      "target": "; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ; ;",
      "finger": "pink",
      "title": "The semicolon",
      "hint": "Right pinky, resting on the home row. No reach - just press where it already sits."
    },
    {
      "type": "p",
      "text": "And there it is - the full alphabet, every letter under your fingers, with nothing left to find by looking. That is the whole keyboard learned. From here the work is no longer about reaching new keys; it is about making the ones you know quick, quiet, and sure. Read each word whole and type it without a glance down."
    },
    {
      "type": "pullquote",
      "text": "The alphabet is the easy part. The craft is in the thousand small, clean keystrokes after it - a little every day, and one morning the keyboard simply disappears.",
      "by": "Eleanor Hayes, editor"
    },
    {
      "type": "step",
